{# FAQ #}
<section class="py-16 bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <h2 class="section-heading text-center mb-10">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4" id="faq-list">

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">Do I need health insurance as a tech worker relocating to Europe?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>Yes, nearly every European country requires residents to have health insurance. In most EU countries, employed tech workers are automatically enrolled in the public system through payroll deductions. In some countries like Germany and the Netherlands, registration with a specific insurer is mandatory within your first few months. Switzerland requires you to purchase private basic insurance independently within 3 months of arrival.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">Which European country has the best healthcare for expats?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>The Netherlands, Denmark, and France consistently rank among the best for expat healthcare. The Netherlands offers an efficient, English-friendly system with short wait times. Denmark provides completely tax-funded healthcare with no out-of-pocket GP visits. France is rated #1 by the WHO for overall system quality. See our <a href="/resources/country-guides/netherlands/">Netherlands guide</a> for more details.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">How much does health insurance cost for expats in Europe?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>Costs vary significantly by country. In tax-funded systems like the UK, Denmark, and Sweden, healthcare is essentially free at the point of use (funded through taxes). In Germany, public insurance costs around 14.6% of gross salary (split with employer). In the Netherlands, basic insurance runs &euro;120-150/month. Switzerland is the most expensive at &euro;300-500/month for mandatory private insurance. Use our <a href="/tools/salary-calculator/">salary calculator</a> to factor in these costs.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">Can I use my home country's health insurance in Europe?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>Generally no — most countries require you to enroll in their local system once you become a resident and start working. Travel insurance or home-country insurance may cover you temporarily during your first weeks, but it's not a long-term solution. EU citizens can use the European Health Insurance Card (EHIC) for temporary stays, but not as a substitute for local insurance once residing in a new country.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

